  "prompt": "Frontal lobe seizure?",
  "response": "Frontal lobe seizures are a type of **focal seizure** that originate in the frontal lobe of the brain. The frontal lobe is responsible for controlling important functions such as movement, decision-making, problem-solving, and emotions. As a result, seizures in this area can cause a wide range of symptoms depending on the specific part of the frontal lobe affected.\n\n### Symptoms of Frontal Lobe Seizures\nSymptoms can vary widely but often include:\n1. **Motor Symptoms**:\n   - Sudden, uncontrolled movements (e.g., arm or leg jerking, bicycling movements of the legs, or thrashing).\n   - Tonic (stiffening) or clonic (jerking) movements.\n   - Unusual posturing or repetitive gestures.\n2. **Behavioral and Emotional Changes**:\n   - Sudden outbursts of emotion (e.g., laughing, crying, or shouting).\n   - Aggressive or agitated behavior.\n   - Speech difficulties (e.g., inability to speak or nonsensical speech).\n3. **Cognitive Symptoms**:\n   - Confusion or altered awareness.\n   - Difficulty with memory or attention.\n4. **Duration**:\n   - Frontal lobe seizures are often brief, lasting less than 30 seconds, and may cluster in quick succession.\n5. **Nocturnal Occurrence**:\n   - These seizures often occur during sleep, and the person may not remember them.\n6. **Other Symptoms**:\n   - Head turning or eye deviation.\n   - Autonomic symptoms (e.g., rapid heart rate, sweating).\n\n### Causes of Frontal Lobe Seizures\n- **Structural Abnormalities**:\n  - Brain tumors, scars from injury, or malformations in the frontal lobe.\n- **Genetic Factors**:\n  - Inherited epilepsy syndromes (e.g., autosomal dominant nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy).\n- **Infections or Inflammation**:\n  - Encephalitis or meningitis.\n- **Stroke or Traumatic Brain Injury**:\n  - Damage to the frontal lobe.\n\n### Diagnosis\nDiagnosing frontal lobe seizures can be challenging because they often mimic other conditions (e.g., psychiatric disorders or sleep disorders). Key diagnostic tools include:\n- **Electroencephalogram (EEG)**: May show abnormal electrical activity in the frontal lobe, though findings can be subtle or normal between seizures.\n- **Brain Imaging (MRI or CT)**: To identify structural abnormalities.\n- **Video EEG Monitoring**: To capture seizures and correlate symptoms with brain activity.\n\n### Treatment\nTreatment aims to control seizures and improve quality of life. Options include:\n1. **Anti-Seizure Medications (ASMs)**:\n   - Commonly used medications include carbamazepine, lamotrigine, levetiracetam, and others.\n2. **Surgery**:\n   - If seizures are drug-resistant and localized to a specific area, surgery to remove the affected tissue may be an option.\n3. **Lifestyle Modifications**:\n   - Managing triggers (e.g., stress, lack of sleep) and maintaining a healthy lifestyle.\n4. **Vagus Nerve Stimulation (VNS)** or **Responsive Neurostimulation (RNS)**:\n   - For refractory epilepsy.\n\nIf you or someone you know is experiencing symptoms of frontal lobe seizures, consult a neurologist for proper evaluation and management. Early diagnosis and treatment are key to minimizing the impact of seizures on daily life.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
